---- DATA STRUCTURES ----

>> A1: Copy here the declaration of each new or changed `struct' or
>> `struct' member, global or static variable, `typedef', or
>> enumeration.  Identify the purpose of each in 25 words or less.

int64_t wake_tick;   /* Tick at which this thread should be unblocked. */
static struct list sleep_list; /* Ordered list of sleeping threads, sorted by wake_tick ascending. */

---- ALGORITHMS ----

>> A2: Briefly describe what happens in a call to timer_sleep(),
>> including the effects of the timer interrupt handler.

The calling thread computes wake_tick = timer_ticks() + ticks and stores it in its own thread struct.
Interrupts are disabled (briefly) while the thread is inserted into sleep_list in ascending wake_tick order using list_insert_ordered.
thread_block() is called, which deschedules the thread and re-enables interrupts — the thread is now fully asleep.

On every timer tick, timer_interrupt() (the interrupt handler) inspects the front of sleep_list. While the front thread's wake_tick ≤ timer_ticks(), it calls thread_unblock() on that thread and pops it from the list, moving it back onto the ready queue.

>> A3: What steps are taken to minimize the amount of time spent in
>> the timer interrupt handler?

sleep_list is kept sorted by wake_tick at insertion time.
 This means the interrupt handler only has to check (and pop) threads from the front of the list
  — it stops as soon as it finds a thread whose wake_tick is still in the future. No full list scan ever occurs inside the interrupt.

---- SYNCHRONIZATION ----

>> A4: How are race conditions avoided when multiple threads call
>> timer_sleep() simultaneously?

Each call to timer_sleep() disables interrupts before inserting the thread into sleep_list and re-enables them only after thread_block() returns.
Because interrupt disabling is per-CPU and Pintos is single-core, two threads cannot run simultaneously.
If thread A is mid-insert, thread B cannot be scheduled until A blocks and interrupts are restored, so the list is never corrupted.

>> A5: How are race conditions avoided when a timer interrupt occurs
>> during a call to timer_sleep()?

Interrupts are disabled before sleep_list is touched and only re-enabled inside thread_block() after the thread is fully on the list.
If the interrupt were to fire at any earlier point, the sleeping thread would not yet be on sleep_list — but that is safe because the tick counter will still be checked on the next interrupt. 
The window of vulnerability (between computing wake_tick and calling thread_block) is protected by the interrupt-disable, so the handler cannot observe a half-inserted entry.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> A6: Why did you choose this design?  In what ways is it superior to
>> another design you considered?

We chose an ordered sleep list plus thread blocking because it avoids busy waiting entirely and keeps CPU time available for runnable threads.
Compared to a loop that repeatedly calls thread_yield(), this design is more efficient, cleaner to reason about, and aligns with the assignment requirement to avoid busy waiting.
Ordering by wake_tick also minimizes timer-interrupt work because the handler only checks the list front until it reaches a future wake time.

