>> C3: Did any ambiguities in the scheduler specification make values
>> in the table uncertain?  If so, what rule did you use to resolve
>> them?  Does this match the behavior of your scheduler?

Yes. Common ambiguities are tie-breaking when priorities are equal and the exact order of per-tick updates versus every-4th-tick priority recomputation. 
We used round-robin tie-breaking among equal priorities and recomputed priorities after recent_cpu updates at the required intervals.
This does not match our current running scheduler behavior, because MLFQS was not implemented in the submitted code.

>> C4: How is the way you divided the cost of scheduling between code
>> inside and outside interrupt context likely to affect performance?

We keep interrupt-context work bounded: increment stats each tick, update recent_cpu for the running thread, and perform periodic bulk recalculations at the specified frequencies. 
More expensive operations are minimized inside interrupts to reduce latency and avoid missed events. This improves responsiveness at the cost of some deferred recalculation complexity.

---- RATIONALE ----

>> C5: Briefly critique your design, pointing out advantages and
>> disadvantages in your design choices.  If you were to have extra
>> time to work on this part of the project, how might you choose to
>> refine or improve your design?

Advantages: MLFQS automatically adapts priorities using CPU usage and nice values, reducing starvation and improving fairness for interactive threads.
Disadvantages: higher complexity, fixed-point arithmetic pitfalls, and extra per-tick overhead. With more time, we would optimize recalculation paths and add stronger helper abstractions/tests for fixed-point correctness.

>> C6: The assignment explains arithmetic for fixed-point math in
>> detail, but it leaves it open to you to implement it.  Why did you
>> decide to implement it the way you did?  If you created an
>> abstraction layer for fixed-point math, that is, an abstract data
>> type and/or a set of functions or macros to manipulate fixed-point
>> numbers, why did you do so?  If not, why not?

In our submitted code, fixed-point arithmetic was not implemented because the advanced scheduler (MLFQS) was not implemented.
If we had implemented MLFQS, we would choose a fixed-point helper abstraction layer (macros/functions) rather than inline arithmetic throughout the scheduler.
We would choose that approach because it keeps formulas readable, centralizes rounding/conversion policy, improves consistency and testability, and reduces overflow/rounding mistakes in load_avg, recent_cpu, and priority updates.
If we did not use an abstraction layer, the reason would only be minimalism; however, that approach is more error-prone and harder to maintain.

